'''Gerrit Alan Cole''' (born September 8, 1990 in [[Newport Beach, California]]) is an American professional baseball [[pitcher]] in the [[Pittsburgh Pirates]] organization. He was selected by the Pirates with the 1st overall selection in the [[2011 Major League Baseball Draft]]. He attended the [[University of California, Los Angeles]] (UCLA), where he pitched for the [[UCLA Bruins baseball|UCLA Bruins]].

==Amateur career==
===High school career===
Cole attended [[Orange Lutheran High School]]. In his sophomore year, Cole pitched for the school's [[junior varsity]] baseball team, allowing no [[run (baseball)|runs]] in 45 [[innings pitched]]. He gained national attention while pitching for the [[varsity team]] in his junior year, as his [[fastball]] reached {{convert|94|mph}}.<ref name=growth>http://www.post-gazette.com/stories/sports/pirates/gerrit-cole-growth-of-a-no-1-draft-pick-221895/?p=0</ref> He reached {{convert|96|mph}} in a showcase for the best [[Prep schools|prep school]] talents, and close to 50 [[scout (sports)|scouts]] attended the first game of his senior season.<ref name=growth/> In his senior year, Cole pitched to a 8-2 [[win-loss record (pitching)|win-loss record]] and a 0.47 [[earned run average]] (ERA), while also recording 121 [[strikeout]]s in 75 innings.<ref>http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20080815&content_id=3313861&vkey=news_mlb&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb</ref>

Cole was named to the [[USA Today All-USA high school baseball team]].  ''[[Baseball America]]'' rated him the 17th best prospect. He was named the [[ESPN]] Rise Athlete of the Month for three consecutive months in March, April, and May 2010.{{Citation needed|date=June 2011}} He was named the [[starting pitcher]] of the 2008 [[Orange County]] North-South All-Star Game.<ref>http://www.ocvarsity.com/sports/strong-8998-kyle-orange.html</ref>

After his senior year, the [[New York Yankees]] selected Cole in the first round, with the 28th overall selection, of the [[2008 Major League Baseball Draft]], becoming the first player ever drafted out of [[Orange Lutheran High School]].  The Yankees, planning on offering Cole a bonus above the recommended amount for the slot, waited until the deadline to attempt to sign Cole{{Citation needed|date=April 2011}}, by which time Cole had decided to follow through with his commitment to attend the [[University of California, Los Angeles]] (UCLA) on a [[college baseball]] scholarship.<ref name=kepner1>{{cite news|last=Kepner |first=Tyler |url=http://bats.blogs.nytimes.com/2008/08/14/first-round-pick-gerrit-cole-opts-for-college-over-yankees/ |title=First Round Pick Gerrit Cole Opts For College Over Yankees |publisher=Bats.blogs.nytimes.com |date=2008-08-14 |accessdate=2011-09-21}}</ref><ref name=kepner2>{{cite news|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2011/04/04/sports/baseball/04pitcher.html|work=New York Times|title=The One That Got Away Is Still a Yankees Fan, and a Hot Pitching Prospect|first=Tyler|last=Kepner|date=April 3, 2011|accessdate=April 4, 2011}}</ref>  Despite being represented by [[Scott Boras]], and though the Yankees were believed to be ready to offer upwards of $4 million, Cole never negotiated with the Yankees, as he was determined to attend college.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2008/writers/jon_heyman/08/18/heyman.cubs/index.html | work=CNN | title=Cubs and Sweet Lou giving their fans reason to believe - Jon Heyman - SI.com | date=August 18, 2008}}</ref>

===College career===
[[John Savage (baseball)|John Savage]], [[coach (baseball)|coach]] of the [[UCLA Bruins baseball|UCLA Bruins]], made Cole the team's Friday night [[starting pitcher]] in his freshman year.<ref name=growth/> That season, Cole recorded a 4-8 win-loss record with a 3.49 ERA, collecting 104 strikeouts in 85 innings. Cole was a member of the 2009 [[United States national baseball team|United States collegiate national baseball team]] and was named to the 2010 Collegiate National Team roster.<ref>[http://web.usabaseball.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20100701&content_id=11806084&vkey=news_usab&gid= 2010 CNT Trials roster announced], ''USABaseball.com'', July 1, 2010</ref><ref>[http://web.usabaseball.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20100711&content_id=12214212&vkey=recap_usab 2010 CNT roster announced ], ''USABaseball.com'', July 11, 2010</ref><ref>http://sports.espn.go.com/los-angeles/news/story?id=4987239</ref>

During the 2010 season, Cole and [[Trevor Bauer]] contributed in making the Bruins the best [[2010 UCLA Bruins baseball team|baseball team]] (51-17 record) in school history and the second best team in the country. Cole had a 11-4 win-loss record, a 3.37 ERA, and 153 strikeouts in 123 innings.<ref name=growth/> His 153 strikeouts placed Cole third in among all collegiate pitchers.<ref>http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2011/writers/joe_lemire/02/21/college.cole.purke.rendon/</ref> The Bruins went on to play in the [[2010 College World Series]], but were defeated by [[South Carolina Gamecocks baseball|South Carolina]] in the [[2010 College World Series#Monday, June 28|NCAA Championship Series]].<ref>http://sports.espn.go.com/losangeles/news/story?id=5338526</ref>

Cole's statistics declined in 2011, his junior year. He finished the season with a 6-8 win-loss record and a 3.31 ERA.<ref>http://www.utsandiego.com/news/2011/jun/06/pirates-hope-top-pick-cole-becomes-big-league-ace/</ref>

==Professional career==
Cole was selected with the first overall pick in the [[2011 Major League Baseball Draft|2011 Major League Baseball (MLB) Draft]] by the [[Pittsburgh Pirates]].  He signed a minor league contract with an $8 million signing bonus fifteen minutes before the signing deadline on August 15, 2011.<ref>{{cite web|title=Pirates ink No. 1 pick Cole, second-rounder Bell|url=http://pittsburgh.pirates.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20110816&content_id=23270806&vkey=news_pit&c_id=pit|date=August 16, 2011|accessdate=2011-08-16|first=Jenifer|last=Langosch|publisher=MLB.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Cole and Pirates Agree at $8 Million|url=http://www.nytimes.com/aponline/2011/08/15/sports/baseball/AP-BBO-Draft-Deadline.html?ref=baseball|date=August 16, 2011|accessdate=2011-08-16|publisher=The New York Times}}</ref> Though he signed too late to pitch in the 2011 minor league season, he pitched for the [[Mesa Solar Sox]] of the [[Arizona Fall League]] (AFL). He recorded 16 [[strikeouts]] in 15 [[innings pitched]] for the Solar Sox and had a 3.00 [[earned run average]] (ERA) and a 0.93 [[walks plus hits per inning pitched]] ratio. He was selected to start the AFL Rising Stars game in November 2011.<ref>[http://pittsburgh.pirates.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20111101&content_id=25862838&vkey=news_pit&c_id=pit= Cole selected to start AFL Rising Stars Game], ''mlb.com'', November 1, 2011</ref>

Cole started the 2012 season with the [[Bradenton Marauders]] of the [[Class A-Advanced]] [[Florida State League]], along with fellow starting pitcher [[Jameson Tallion]], the Pirates' first selection in the [[2010 MLB Draft]].<ref>http://www.post-gazette.com/stories/sports/pirates/pirates-prospects-taillon-cole-learning-patience-will-take-them-places-632320/</ref> Cole was named a FSL Mid-Season All-Star. He was promoted to the [[Altoona Curve]] of the [[Class AA (baseball)|Class AA]] [[Eastern League]] on June 15, 2012.<ref>[http://pittsburgh.pirates.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20120615&content_id=33354982&notebook_id=33360748&vkey=notebook_pit&c_id=pit= Cole promoted to Double-A Altoona], ''mlb.com'', June 15, 2012</ref> He was named to appear in the 2012 [[All-Star Futures Game]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20120620&content_id=33663130&vkey=news_mlb&c_id=mlb |title=Prospects pack rosters for 2012 All-Star Futures Game &#124; MLB.com: News |publisher=Mlb.mlb.com |date=2012-06-19 |accessdate=2012-08-30}}</ref> In twelve starts with the Curve, Cole pitched to a 2.90 ERA, before the Pirates promoted him to the [[Indianapolis Indians]] of the [[Triple-A (baseball)|Class AAA]] [[International League]] on August 29, 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.altoonamirror.com/page/blogs.detail/display/5533/Pirates-promote-Gerrit-Cole-from-Curve-to-Triple-A.html|title=Pirates promote Gerrit Cole from Curve to Triple-A|publisher=The Altoona Mirror|last=Giger|first=Cory|date=August 29, 2012|accessdate=2012-08-30}}</ref>

==Scouting report==
Cole features a fastball that he regularly throws between {{convert|94|to(-)|98|mph}}, but has been clocked as high as {{convert|102|mph}}.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://content.usatoday.com/communities/dailypitch/post/2011/06/live-mlb-draft-tracker-gerrit-cole-danny-hultzen/1|work=USA Today|title=Pirates select Gerrit Cole No. 1 overall; pick-by-pick of the draft|date=June 6, 2011|accessdate=July 30, 2011}}</ref> He also throws a slider and a changeup.<ref>[http://www.nydailynews.com/sports/baseball/yankees/2008/06/05/2008-06-05_yankees_take_gerrit_cole_with_1st_rd_pic-4.html Yankees take Gerrit Cole with 1st rd. pick in MLB draft], ''NY Daily News'', June 6, 2008</ref>

==Personal==
Cole has a younger sister, Erin.<ref name=growth/> He grew up as a fan of the Yankees, and attended the [[2001 World Series]].<ref name=kepner1/><ref name=kepner2/>

